Notable Deals

26 projects collectively raised $267 million last week. Here are eight that stood out:

World Foundation

  • The Pitch: A proof-of-personhood protocol enabling a universal digital ID and global financial access
  • Round: $135 million Public Token Sale
  • Investors: Led by a16z crypto and Bain Capital Crypto, with participation from Mirana Ventures, Selini Capital, and Arctic Digital

Catena Labs

  • The Pitch: Building an AI-native financial institution
  • Round: $18 million Seed
  • Investors: Led by a16z crypto with participation from Coinbase Ventures, Circle Ventures, Breyer Capital, and more

Roxom

  • The Pitch: Developing a Bitcoin-denominated exchange
  • Round: $17.9 million funding
  • Investors: Borderless Capital, Draper Associates, Kingsway Capital, and Ego Death Capital

True Markets

  • The Pitch: A mobile-first, stablecoin-native DeFi trading app on Solana
  • Round: $11 million Series A
  • Investors: Led by Accomplice and RRE Ventures, with participation from Variant, Reciprocal Ventures, PayPal Ventures, Solana Foundation, and Paxos

Hyperdrive

  • The Pitch: Stablecoin money market for Hyperliquid
  • Round: $6 million Series A
  • Investors: Led by Hack VC and Arrington Capital, with participation from CMS Holdings, Amber Group, Delphi Ventures, and more

VOYA Games

  • The Pitch: Crypto gaming studio developing Craft World
  • Round: $5 million funding
  • Investors: Led by 1kx and Makers Fund, with participation from RockawayX, Sebastien Borget, and more

Rover

  • The Pitch: Building a Bitcoin liquid staking platform on Botanix
  • Round: $4.1 million Seed
  • Investors: Animoca Brands, CMS Holdings, MH Ventures, Infinity Ventures Crypto, Cogitent Ventures, Maelstrom, and more

ARAI

  • The Pitch: Developing an AI-native co-pilot system for gaming
  • Round: $4 million Seed
  • Investors: Animoca Brands, Sequoia Capital, Folius Ventures, Gate Ventures, Skyland Ventures, and more

M&A Activity

DePIN Pulse acquired DePIN.Ninja and Who Loves Burrito

DePIN Pulse acquired DePIN.Ninja and Who Loves Burrito in a strategic consolidation aimed at streamlining the fragmented DePIN ecosystem data. The acquisitions unify key infrastructure insights into a single dashboard, DePIN Pulse V2, which offers real-time analytics across multiple blockchains, early-stage project discovery, mining and yield opportunity tracking, and a decentralized compute marketplace.

Alchemy acquired HeyMint

Alchemy acquired NFT launchpad HeyMint as part of its broader push to scale its Smart Wallets offering and streamline Web3 onboarding. HeyMint provides no-code tools for NFT collection creation and community growth across Ethereum and Layer-2 networks. Since its launch, HeyMint has supported over 40,000 creators and facilitated $38 million in revenue.

Apex Group acquired Tokeny

Fund administrator Apex Group announced plans to acquire 100% of tokenization firm Tokeny over a three-year period, deepening its commitment to digital asset infrastructure. A strategic investor since 2023, Apex aims to integrate Tokenyâ€™s SaaS platform and its T-REX ERC-3643 token standard into its broader fund administration services. Tokeny has supported over $32 billion in asset tokenizations, with clients including ABN AMRO and Inveniam.

Funds

Theta Blockchain Ventures IV â€“ $175M

Theta Capital Management raised $175 million for Theta Blockchain Ventures IV, a fund-of-funds backing crypto-native VCs focused on early-stage blockchain startups. The fund targets specialist managers like Polychain Capital, CoinFund, and Castle Island Ventures, aiming to leverage their compounded expertise and edge in early-stage investing. Theta, which pivoted to digital assets in 2018, sees dedicated crypto VCs as better positioned than generalists to navigate and capitalize on the sectorâ€™s resurgence.

James Ho (Modular Capital)

  • Published a thesis arguing Pendle is the leading indexed exposure to the rise of yield-bearing stablecoins, capturing 30% of the segmentâ€™s TVL and benefiting structurally from regulatory clarity and market expansion.

Emma Cui (LongHash Ventures)

  • Argues that despite recent market disillusionment, crypto VC is undergoing a necessary reset, moving from speculative excess toward a more disciplined, product-market fit-driven cycle poised for long-term institutional relevance.

Mads Mathiesen (Maven 11)

  • Explores the design trade-offs of Multiple Concurrent Proposers (MCP) as a mechanism to improve censorship resistance, decentralize MEV, and scale base layer throughput, while acknowledging challenges around ordering complexity, hardware demands, and finality coordination.
